  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "So I might be asking a silly question, but how do I view the source of a cookie?",
  "response": "Not a silly question at all! Viewing the source of a cookie isn't straightforward because cookies are stored and handled by your web browser, not directly in the HTML source code of a webpage. However, you can view the details of cookies in your browser using developer tools. Here's how:\n\n### **1. Using Browser Developer Tools**\n#### **Chrome, Edge, or Brave Browser:**\n1. Open the website where the cookie is set.\n2. Right-click anywhere on the page and select **Inspect** (or press `Ctrl+Shift+I` / `Cmd+Option+I` on Mac).\n3. Go to the **Application** tab (or **Storage** in some older versions).\n4. In the left sidebar, expand **Cookies** and select the website.\n5. You\u2019ll see a list of cookies for that site, including their **Name**, **Value**, **Domain**, **Path**, **Expiration**, and other attributes.\n\n#### **Firefox:**\n1. Open the website where the cookie is set.\n2. Right-click anywhere on the page and select **Inspect** (or press `Ctrl+Shift+I` / `Cmd+Option+I` on Mac).\n3. Go to the **Storage** tab.\n4. Expand **Cookies** and select the website.\n5. You\u2019ll see the cookies listed with their **Name**, **Value**, **Domain**, **Path**, **Expiration**, etc.\n\n#### **Safari:**\n1. Enable the Develop menu by going to Safari > Preferences > Advanced, and check \"Show Develop menu in menu bar.\"\n2. Open the website where the cookie is set.\n3. Go to the **Develop** menu and select **Show Web Inspector** (or press `Cmd+Option+I`).\n4. Go to the **Storage** tab.\n5. Expand **Cookies** and select the website to view the cookies.\n\n### **2. Viewing Cookies via Browser Settings**\nYou can also view cookies directly in your browser\u2019s settings, but this method is less precise for specific websites:\n- **Chrome**: `Settings > Privacy and Security > Cookies and other site data > See all site data and permissions`\n- **Firefox**: `Settings > Privacy & Security > Cookies and Site Data > Manage Data`\n- **Safari**: `Safari Preferences > Privacy > Manage Website Data`\n\n### **3. Viewing the HTTP Header (Server-Side)**\nCookies are sent to the browser via HTTP headers. If you want to see how the cookie is set by the server:\n- Use a tool like **Postman** or **cURL** to inspect the HTTP response headers.\n- Look for the `Set-Cookie` header in the response.\n\n### **4. Decoding Cookie Values**\nSometimes, cookie values are encoded (e.g., Base64 or URL-encoded). You can use online tools or built-in JavaScript functions like `atob()` (for Base64) to decode them.\n\nLet me know if you need further clarification! \ud83d\ude0a",
  "temperature": 1.0,
